- "Higher-than-average CPU usage" refers to servers whose average CPU usage is above the overall average CPU usage across all servers.;
- The CPU usage is calculated by summing the time spent in user mode, system mode, nice mode, and gnice mode.;
- The final result includes only the names of the servers meeting this criterion.

- "born after the last report's creation" refers to servers whose metrics were recorded after the latest report was generated;
- "carry a heavier load than the baseline" means the average 1-minute load of the server is greater than the average 1-minute load of the reference server (server_id = 0);
- "rank in terms of their burden" refers to the ordering of the servers based on their average 1-minute load in descending order.

- "recently" refers to the latest records based on timestamps;
- "attracted more than one unique visitor" means the count of distinct user IDs is greater than 1;
- "whisper in the digital forest" refers to the latest memory usage percentage.

- "busiest bee in the hive" refers to the server with the highest resource usage and the most alerts;
- "CPU usage" is the percentage of CPU time used, calculated from system and user mode time;
- "alerts" are notifications or warnings generated by the server, indicating potential issues or events.

- High CPU usage is defined as greater than 80%;
- High memory usage is defined as greater than 70%;
- Significant disk activity is defined as more than 1,000,000 bytes read;
- Frequent alerts are defined as more than 5 alerts generated.

- "Top 3" refers to the highest ranks;
- "Average 1-minute load" is calculated from the `load_1m` column;
- "Overall average 1-minute load" is the average of all `load_1m` values across all servers.

- Disk usage category is determined by comparing total disk write to total disk read;
- 'High' category indicates more data is being written than read;
- 'Low' category indicates more data is being read than written;
- 'Medium' category indicates equal read and write activity.

- 'Daily average performance metrics' include memory usage, disk I/O, network I/O, and CPU temperature;
- 'Alert counts' are the total number of alerts and specific types of alerts (CPU usage, memory usage, disk I/O, network I/O);
- 'Current status and details' include server name, status, location, IP address, hardware model, OS version, total CPU cores, total memory, total disk space, last maintenance date, next maintenance date, and maintenance status.

- "active" servers are those currently operational and not under maintenance;
- The `memory_used / memory_total` ratio indicates the percentage of memory being utilized;
- The 1-minute load average (`load_1m`) measures the average system load over the past minute.

- "top 3 servers by memory usage" refers to the servers with the highest average memory usage percentage;
- "average memory usage" is calculated as the total memory used divided by the total memory available, expressed as a percentage;
- "average disk I/O" is the average number of bytes read and written per performance metric.

sql:
SELECT server_name
FROM servers
WHERE server_id > 0;

SELECT server_name, total_memory_gb
FROM servers
WHERE total_memory_gb = (
  SELECT MAX(total_memory_gb)
  FROM servers
);
